<section id="definitions">
  <h2>What are SEO and AEO?</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">SEO improves a website's ability to be discovered, understood and selected in search. Answer engine optimisation applies many of the same foundations while paying closer attention to how information is extracted, corroborated and cited inside generated or direct answers.</p>
  <p>Terminology is inconsistent. AEO can mean answer engine optimisation. GEO usually means generative engine optimisation. AI SEO and LLM optimisation are broad commercial labels. Different platforms use different crawlers, indexes, retrieval methods and reporting, so no acronym describes one universal ranking system.</p>
  <p>The useful distinction is practical:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>SEO foundation:</strong> crawlability, indexability, site architecture, search intent, useful pages, links, performance, entities and authority.</li>
    <li><strong>Answer layer:</strong> direct explanations, self-contained sections, sourceable evidence, clear entity relationships and measurement of citations, mentions and AI referrals.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>This is not a choice between writing for humans and formatting for machines. Clear, well-supported information helps people make decisions and makes it easier for systems to interpret the same page accurately.</p>
  <div class="article-callout">
    <span>CNVRT position</span>
    <p><strong>AEO extends a good SEO programme.</strong> If the site cannot be crawled, the offer is unclear and the content adds nothing original, adding question headings or extra schema will not create durable authority.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="official-position">
  <h2>What do search and answer platforms actually say?</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">The current primary-source guidance is more measured than many commercial AEO claims. Google says its existing SEO best practices remain relevant to AI Overviews and AI Mode, with no additional technical requirements or special AI markup.</p>
  <h3>Google Search and AI features</h3>
  <p>Google says a page must be indexed and eligible to appear in Search with a snippet to be eligible as a supporting link in AI features. Its guidance recommends crawlable pages, contextual internal links, a good page experience, important information in text, useful media and structured data that matches the visible content. It explicitly says no new machine-readable AI file or special schema is required. See <a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/ai-features">Google's AI features guidance</a>.</p>
  <p>Google also describes query fan-out, where an AI experience may issue several related searches across subtopics and sources. That strengthens the case for useful coverage of a subject and a connected site architecture. It does not justify publishing a separate thin page for every wording of the same question.</p>
  <h3>Bing and Microsoft Copilot</h3>
  <p>Microsoft's Bing Webmaster Tools now includes AI Performance reporting for supported experiences. It reports citations, cited pages and grounding queries, while warning that citation counts do not indicate placement or authority inside an individual answer. Microsoft recommends depth, clear structure, evidence and accurate updates. See <a href="https://blogs.bing.com/webmaster/February-2026/Introducing-AI-Performance-in-Bing-Webmaster-Tools-Public-Preview">Bing's AI Performance announcement</a>.</p>
  <h3>ChatGPT Search</h3>
  <p>OpenAI says public websites can appear in ChatGPT search, and publishers can use robots controls for OAI-SearchBot. Referral URLs include <code>utm_source=chatgpt.com</code>, which provides one measurable signal. ChatGPT visibility is not a single fixed ranking position, and the result can change with the question, context and system. See the <a href="https://help.openai.com/en/articles/12627856-publishers-and-developers-faq">OpenAI publishers and developers FAQ</a>.</p>
  <h3>Perplexity</h3>
  <p>Perplexity documents PerplexityBot as a crawler used to surface and link websites in search results, with published crawler and robots information. Its behaviour should be assessed from current documentation rather than assuming it matches Google or Bing. See <a href="https://docs.perplexity.ai/docs/resources/perplexity-crawlers">Perplexity's crawler documentation</a>.</p>
</section>

<section id="shared-foundation">
  <h2>The foundation SEO and AEO share</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">A reliable combined programme begins with accessibility to crawlers, unambiguous page purpose, substantial information, evidence and connected authority. These are not new requirements created by generative search.</p>
  <div class="article-framework">
    <article><div><span>01</span><h3>Discovery</h3></div><p>Important pages need crawlable HTML links, stable URLs, sensible canonicals, accurate sitemaps and robots controls that reflect the intended visibility.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>02</span><h3>Clear ownership</h3></div><p>Each page should own one coherent intent. Consolidate overlapping articles instead of making several weak pages compete to answer the same question.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>03</span><h3>Useful information</h3></div><p>Resolve the reader's task with direct answers, enough depth, examples, limitations and a practical next action. Do not write to an arbitrary word count.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>04</span><h3>First-hand value</h3></div><p>Add real decisions, project learning, original frameworks, controlled data, screenshots or tools that a generic summary cannot reproduce.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>05</span><h3>Trust and entities</h3></div><p>Make the business, people, services and evidence clear and consistent, then support important claims with primary sources and relevant external corroboration.</p></article>
    <article><div><span>06</span><h3>Page experience</h3></div><p>Keep essential information visible in HTML, mobile reading comfortable, navigation accessible, media useful and intrusive promotion away from the main answer.</p></article>
  </div>
  <p>Google's people-first guidance asks whether content provides original information or analysis, gives a substantial description, demonstrates first-hand knowledge and leaves the reader feeling they have learned enough to achieve their goal. It also states there is no preferred word count. See <a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/fundamentals/creating-helpful-content">Google's helpful-content self-assessment</a>.</p>
  <p>Internal linking is part of this foundation. Use descriptive links from service pages, topic hubs, related guides and case studies where the destination genuinely helps. Google says every important page should receive a link from at least one other page and that no magical ideal number of links exists.</p>
</section>

<section id="differences">
  <h2>What genuinely changes for AI answers?</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">The answer layer changes how questions are researched, how sections are written and how visibility is measured. It does not replace the underlying site and authority work.</p>
  <div class="article-table-wrap">
    <table class="article-table">
      <caption>SEO and answer-engine emphasis</caption>
      <thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Established SEO emphasis</th><th>Additional answer-engine emphasis</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Intent research</td><td>Queries, pages, journeys, competitors and commercial value.</td><td>Natural-language follow-up questions, comparison needs and subtopics used during wider exploration.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Content structure</td><td>Descriptive titles, headings, complete pages and internal links.</td><td>Self-contained answers, clear definitions, tables, steps and claims that retain meaning when cited out of context.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Evidence</td><td>Experience, expertise, links, references and demonstrable trust.</td><td>Source proximity, explicit attribution, entity clarity and information another system can verify across sources.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Off-site presence</td><td>Relevant links, mentions, reviews, profiles and reputation.</td><td>Consistent corroboration across the third-party sources answer systems may retrieve.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Measurement</td><td>Impressions, rankings, clicks, conversions, revenue and assisted value.</td><td>Citations, cited pages, prompt observations, AI referral traffic, brand mentions and their commercial contribution.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>Do not reduce this to writing shorter paragraphs. A concise answer can introduce a complex issue, but it still needs supporting reasoning, evidence and exceptions. A migration risk, legal requirement or strategic comparison often cannot be served accurately in fifty words.</p>
  <h3>Question mapping should follow one intent</h3>
  <p>Map the main question, necessary definitions, suitability, process, alternatives, risks, limitations, measurement and next action. Keep questions that help the same reader complete the same task. A materially different commercial or informational intent deserves another page.</p>
  <h3>Write sections that can stand on their own</h3>
  <p>Begin an important section with a direct answer, then explain why, add evidence and state where the advice changes. Descriptive headings help readers scan and reduce ambiguity when a passage is extracted or summarised.</p>
</section>

<section id="content">
  <h2>How do you create content worth citing?</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">A sourceable page says something specific, useful and supportable. It clearly separates documented fact, first-hand experience, professional judgement and uncertainty.</p>
  <h3>Start with information gain</h3>
  <p>Before writing, audit what current results already answer. The opportunity is not a new arrangement of the same definitions. Add something that changes or improves the reader's decision:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>An original checklist or responsibility matrix used in real work.</li>
    <li>An anonymised field-mapping example from a migration.</li>
    <li>A project decision and the constraint that shaped it.</li>
    <li>A controlled dataset with method, sample, date and limitations.</li>
    <li>An annotated screenshot showing what was changed and why.</li>
    <li>A clear comparison that identifies when the recommendation changes.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Put sources beside consequential claims</h3>
  <p>Cite platform rules, laws, statistics and time-sensitive features using original documentation wherever possible. Explain the period and method for first-party performance claims. External references are not a weakness. Google says contextual external links can help establish trustworthiness when they support the reader.</p>
  <h3>Show who is responsible</h3>
  <p>Use a real author with an accurate role and a substantive profile. Display publication and review dates honestly. Add a named reviewer only when that person actually checked the content and has relevant expertise. Google recommends accurate author markup and an author URL on Article structured data.</p>
  <h3>Build and maintain a cluster</h3>
  <p>An anchor guide should resolve the broad task and link to specialist pages where another intent needs more depth. Supporting guides should return to the anchor, commercial service and relevant evidence. Review platform-dependent pages on a defined schedule and consolidate overlap rather than creating a new dated version every year.</p>
  <div class="article-callout article-callout--dark">
    <span>Publication test</span>
    <p>Would this article still be worth publishing if search engines sent no traffic? If it would help a client plan, diagnose or decide, it is more likely to contain the original usefulness authority actually needs.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="technical">
  <h2>Technical SEO, schema and AI crawlers</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">Technical controls make content eligible and understandable. They do not force a search result, citation or recommendation.</p>
  <h3>Crawlability and indexability</h3>
  <p>Check robots.txt, page-level robots directives, canonical URLs, HTTP responses, sitemaps, rendering and internal links. Important content should be present in the rendered HTML. A page that is blocked, noindexed or hidden behind an interaction cannot be rescued by answer-focused copy.</p>
  <h3>Structured data</h3>
  <p>Use supported schema that matches visible information, such as Organisation, Service, Article, Product or BreadcrumbList where appropriate. Article markup can identify the headline, author, dates, image and publisher. It is not a magic AEO tag and does not guarantee a rich result or AI citation.</p>
  <h3>FAQ and Q&amp;A markup</h3>
  <p>Question sections can improve clarity when they answer genuine follow-up needs. Do not add repetitive FAQs solely for keywords. QAPage is for pages where users submit answers to one question, not an agency article. Google now limits FAQ rich-result visibility mainly to authoritative government and health sites, so the reader benefit should be the reason for including an FAQ.</p>
  <h3>Do you need llms.txt?</h3>
  <p>Google says no new AI text file is required for its AI features. Other platforms may publish their own crawler controls, and those controls should be evaluated separately. An experimental file is not a substitute for accessible pages, robots policy, clear ownership and useful content.</p>
  <div class="article-table-wrap">
    <table class="article-table">
      <caption>Common AI-search myths</caption>
      <thead><tr><th>Claim</th><th>More credible position</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>SEO is dead.</td><td>Google and Bing describe search foundations as the basis for discovery and generated answers.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>FAQ schema guarantees citations.</td><td>Structured data can clarify eligible visible content. It does not guarantee selection or citation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Every site needs llms.txt.</td><td>Google explicitly says no special AI file is required. Follow current platform-specific documentation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Longer content always wins.</td><td>There is no preferred word count. The page should complete the reader's task without filler.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Mass AI articles create authority.</td><td>Scaled, unoriginal content increases duplication, factual risk and maintenance cost.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>An agency can guarantee ChatGPT citations.</td><td>Outputs vary by platform, model, prompt, location, time and available sources. A guarantee is not credible.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="authority">
  <h2>Entities, evidence and off-site authority</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">A website cannot establish every claim about itself. Search and answer systems can also encounter reviews, directories, press, professional profiles, client sites and independent references when trying to understand a business or person.</p>
  <p>Make the core entities unambiguous on the owned site: business name, owner, location, services, projects, contact details and relationships. Keep those facts consistent wherever they appear. Mark up genuine organisation and person information, but do not use schema to assert credentials or relationships that are not visible and verifiable.</p>
  <h3>Earn corroboration, do not manufacture it</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Collect detailed, permissioned customer reviews on relevant platforms.</li>
    <li>Publish case studies that clients can confirm and, where appropriate, reference.</li>
    <li>Maintain accurate professional and business profiles.</li>
    <li>Contribute specialist evidence or commentary where it genuinely helps another publication.</li>
    <li>Create original tools, research or frameworks that others have a reason to cite.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Links and mentions remain useful, but relevance and context matter more than counting every domain equally. Avoid mass listings, paid placements disguised as editorial endorsement and synthetic review activity. These weaken trust even if they create short-term references.</p>
  <div class="article-field-note">
    <span>CNVRT field note</span>
    <h3>Use evidence to explain the system, not to overclaim AI visibility.</h3>
    <p>The <a href="/work/hear-better/">Hear Better case study</a> shows how clear local services, clinically informed explanations, trust signals, reviews and connected acquisition support search visibility. It does not yet provide a controlled record of citations across ChatGPT, AI Overviews or other platforms, so CNVRT does not present it as verified AEO performance.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="measurement">
  <h2>How should SEO and AI visibility be measured?</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">Use a combined measurement model. Search visibility, citations and referral traffic are useful signals, but the business outcome still depends on whether the visibility reaches the right audience and contributes to qualified enquiries or revenue.</p>
  <div class="article-table-wrap">
    <table class="article-table">
      <caption>Combined search measurement</caption>
      <thead><tr><th>Layer</th><th>Measures</th><th>Important limitation</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Technical eligibility</td><td>Indexed pages, crawl errors, robots, canonicals, rendering and structured-data validity.</td><td>Eligibility does not guarantee ranking or citation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Search discovery</td><td>Search Console impressions, queries, clicks, landing pages and positions.</td><td>Average positions hide location, device and result-feature variation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>AI references</td><td>Bing citations, cited pages, grounding queries and a controlled prompt-monitoring set.</td><td>Outputs change by platform, prompt, model, date and context.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Referral behaviour</td><td>AI referral sessions, landing pages, engagement and assisted journeys.</td><td>Some answer experiences may create no click and attribution can be incomplete.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Brand demand</td><td>Branded search, direct traffic, reviews, mentions and sales feedback.</td><td>Several activities influence brand demand, so causation needs caution.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Commercial outcome</td><td>Qualified leads, bookings, sales, revenue, margin and assisted conversions.</td><td>CRM quality and agreed attribution matter more than one analytics report.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <h3>Use a controlled prompt record</h3>
  <p>For each monitored question, record the exact prompt, platform, model or mode where visible, date, location, account state, response, cited sources and whether the brand appeared. Repeat tests on a schedule and report volatility. Do not turn a single favourable screenshot into a performance claim.</p>
  <p>Connect visibility to the onsite journey with <a href="/services/analytics-conversion-tracking/">conversion tracking and commercial feedback</a>. A citation is interesting. A citation that helps the right buyer discover a useful page and become a qualified customer is valuable.</p>
</section>

<section id="plan">
  <h2>A practical 90-day SEO and AEO plan</h2>
  <p class="article-lead">Fix eligibility and page ownership first, then improve the information and evidence, then measure across classic and answer-led discovery. The sequence matters because later work depends on a stable foundation.</p>
  <h3>Days 1 to 30: establish the foundation</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Audit crawlability, indexability, canonicals, sitemaps, rendering and important templates.</li>
    <li>Map services, audiences, commercial intents and the page that owns each topic.</li>
    <li>Review organisation, owner, service, location and contact consistency.</li>
    <li>Baseline Search Console, analytics, conversions, Bing and available AI referrals.</li>
    <li>Create a small, controlled prompt set with an honest reporting method.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Days 31 to 60: strengthen the owned evidence</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Improve priority service pages around customer questions, process, evidence and limitations.</li>
    <li>Publish one substantial guide where CNVRT can add direct experience or an original tool.</li>
    <li>Add accurate author, publication, review and Article information.</li>
    <li>Connect guides, services and case studies with useful contextual links.</li>
    <li>Resolve overlapping, outdated or unsupported pages rather than adding volume.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Days 61 to 90: corroborate and learn</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Strengthen client-approved case studies, reviews and relevant external profiles.</li>
    <li>Promote genuinely useful resources to appropriate partners and publications.</li>
    <li>Review citations, search queries, referral journeys and sales feedback together.</li>
    <li>Improve unclear or incomplete sections using real audience questions.</li>
    <li>Choose the next supporting article only when its intent and evidence are distinct.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>CNVRT's <a href="/services/seo/">SEO services</a> address the wider search foundation, while <a href="/services/aeo/">AEO and AI search work</a> adds platform-aware question, evidence and measurement layers. They should share one roadmap and one commercial view.</p>
</section>

<section id="questions">
  <h2>Frequently asked SEO and AEO questions</h2>
  <div class="article-questions">
    <details><summary>Does AEO replace SEO?</summary><p>No. AI search still needs accessible, understandable and trustworthy source material. AEO adds emphasis to direct answers, corroborated entities, citation-friendly evidence and new measurement, but it depends on many established SEO foundations.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Is AEO the same as GEO?</summary><p>The terms overlap and are used inconsistently. AEO often focuses on direct or generated answers, while GEO explicitly refers to generative engines. The label matters less than defining the platforms, work and measures included.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Does schema improve AI visibility?</summary><p>Structured data can help systems understand visible entities and eligible content when it is accurate and supported. Google says no special schema is required for its AI features, and schema does not guarantee an AI citation.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Does a website need an llms.txt file?</summary><p>Google says no new AI text file is required for AI Overviews or AI Mode. Other platforms have their own crawler documentation. Review those controls separately, but prioritise accessible, indexable and useful pages.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Can AI-generated content rank?</summary><p>The production method alone is not the deciding issue. Google focuses on helpfulness and warns against scaled unoriginal content made to manipulate rankings. A responsible human should verify facts, add real expertise, remove repetition and take ownership of the finished work.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Can an agency guarantee a ChatGPT or AI Overview citation?</summary><p>No credible agency can guarantee a result controlled by an external system that varies by prompt, context, platform and time. It can improve the quality, accessibility, evidence and corroboration of the source material, then monitor the outcome honestly.</p></details>
    <details><summary>How long does AEO take?</summary><p>There is no universal period. Technical access, existing authority, content quality, topic competition, platform crawling and external evidence all affect discovery. Agree leading indicators and commercial outcomes rather than a guaranteed deadline.</p></details>
  </div>
</section>

